    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>TRINITY MIRROR BUYS SOUTHNEWS</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Alan Cowell</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Cowell, Alan</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Trinity Mirror buys Southnews, based in wealthy southeastern England, for $409 million (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>As British newspaper groups consolidate to cut costs and broaden advertising revenues, Trinity Mirror, the country's biggest regional publisher, said it agreed to buy Southnews, based in wealthy southeastern England, for $409 million. Trinity Mirror, the acquisitive creation of Trinity's purchase of Mirror Group last year, said the price of 1,200 pence ($17.40) a share represented a 57 percent premium over Southnews's closing price yesterday. Trinity Mirror shares slumped by as much as 2.9 percent, to 452 pence ($6.55), while Southnews stock soared by 54 percent, to 1,175 pence ($17.03).</p>
        <p>Alan Cowell (NYT)</p>
      </block>
